Retail Demand Forecasting & Inventory Replenishment
Decision Memo
1. Business Goal & KPIs
Objective

The objective of this project is to reduce stockouts while controlling excess inventory and holding costs by implementing a data-driven demand forecasting and replenishment system at the SKU–Store level.

Retail businesses often struggle with:

Stockouts → lost sales and poor customer experience

Overstock → tied-up working capital and higher holding costs

This project proposes a forecasting-driven replenishment framework to optimize inventory levels.

North Star Metric

Fill Rate (Service Level)

Fill Rate = Total Demand / Demand Fulfilled
	​


Improving fill rate directly reduces lost sales and improves product availability.

Supporting KPIs

The following metrics were tracked to evaluate the system:

KPI	Purpose
Forecast Accuracy (MAPE / WAPE)	Measures demand prediction accuracy
Stockout Rate	% of days SKU inventory reaches zero
Fill Rate	Ability to meet customer demand
Days of Inventory on Hand (DOH)	Inventory coverage duration
Inventory Turns	Inventory efficiency proxy
Overstock Rate	% of SKUs with DOH above threshold
Holding Cost Proxy	Inventory value × holding rate
Lost Sales Proxy	True demand – actual sales
Safety Stock Level	Buffer inventory required
Reorder Point	Inventory level triggering replenishment
2. Data & Methodology
Data Sources

The system integrates multiple operational datasets:

Dataset	Description
Stores	Store region, size, and tier
Products	SKU category, price, cost, shelf life, MOQ
Sales Daily	SKU-store level daily demand and revenue
Inventory Daily	Opening and closing inventory levels
Purchase Orders	Lead times and historical orders
Calendar	Promotions, holidays, weekday patterns

The dataset contained approximately:

342k sales records

341k inventory records

90 SKUs across 18 stores

ETL Pipeline

The ETL pipeline performs:

Data ingestion from source URLs

Standardization of column formats

Cleaning and missing value handling

Joining product and store attributes

Feature engineering for inventory and demand metrics

Three curated datasets were created:

Dataset	Purpose
fact_sales_store_sku_daily	Core demand dataset
fact_inventory_store_sku_daily	Inventory tracking
replenishment_inputs_store_sku	Inputs for reorder calculations
Forecasting Methodology

Two models were implemented:

1. Baseline Model (Seasonal Naive)

Forecast = demand from the same day in the previous week.

Captures weekly demand seasonality.

2. Regression Forecast Model

Features used:

Promo flag

Holiday flag

Day of week

Month

Lag-1 demand

Lag-7 demand

Rolling mean demand

Rolling demand volatility

The regression model captures:

seasonality

promotions

demand trends

demand volatility

Forecast horizon:

28 days (4 weeks)

3. Key Insights

Analysis of demand and inventory patterns produced the following insights:

1. Strong weekly seasonality

Demand peaks typically occur on weekends, while mid-week demand is lower.

2. Promotions significantly increase demand

Promo periods show meaningful uplift in average units sold, indicating strong price sensitivity.

3. Certain SKUs dominate volume and revenue

A small set of SKUs contribute disproportionately to total sales, indicating a Pareto distribution of demand.

4. Stockouts are concentrated in specific stores

A few store locations account for most stockout occurrences, suggesting local demand forecasting improvements are needed.

5. Demand volatility varies by category

Categories like fresh and produce show higher variability, requiring higher safety stock.

6. Overstock risk occurs for slow-moving SKUs

Products with long shelf life and low demand accumulate excess inventory.

7. Lead time variability drives stockout risk

SKUs with longer supplier lead times require significantly higher safety stock levels.

4. Forecast Performance

Two forecasting approaches were compared:

Model	Strengths
Baseline	Simple, captures weekly patterns
Regression	Incorporates promotions, trends, and volatility

Results show that the regression model generally performs better in categories affected by promotions and holidays.

The final system keeps both models for comparison and selects the better performing one based on WAPE.

5. Replenishment Policy

The replenishment framework uses a Continuous Review (R,Q) policy.

Reorder Point Formula

ROP = Demand avg ×LeadTime + SafetyStock

SafetyStock = Z × DemandStdDev × LeadTime
	​
Where Z corresponds to the service level target by category.

Example targets:

Category	Service Level
Fresh / Produce	98%
Dairy	97%
Frozen	96%
Beverages	95%
Order Quantity
OrderQty = OrderUpToLevel − CurrentInventory

Constraints applied:

Minimum Order Quantity (MOQ)

Shelf-life limits

Demand forecasts

Example Replenishment Output

The system generates:

Recommended PO list

Replenishment policy table

Top stockout risk SKUs

Top overstock risk SKUs

These outputs help planners prioritize inventory actions.

6. 30-Day Impact Estimate

A simulation model estimated the business impact of applying the proposed replenishment system.

Three scenarios were evaluated:

Scenario	Description
Conservative	Partial adoption
Base Case	Recommended policy
Aggressive	Higher service levels

Estimated benefits include:

Reduced lost sales

Improved product availability

Better inventory balance

The base scenario indicates measurable improvements in fill rate and reduced stockout risk.

7. Risks & Limitations
1. Forecast uncertainty

Demand volatility and unexpected demand spikes may reduce forecast accuracy.

2. Supplier variability

Lead times may fluctuate due to supplier delays.

3. Promotion planning changes

Unplanned promotions could distort demand forecasts.

4. Data limitations

Historical data may not capture structural demand changes.

Next Steps

To further improve the system:

Implement automated daily forecast updates

Introduce advanced forecasting models (Prophet / XGBoost)

Integrate real-time inventory monitoring

Incorporate store clustering for demand similarity

Connect replenishment system to automatic purchase order generation

Conclusion

The proposed forecasting and replenishment framework provides a scalable approach to improving retail inventory performance.

By integrating demand forecasting with inventory policies, the system enables:

better product availability

lower lost sales

more efficient inventory management

The approach supports data-driven inventory decisions at the SKU–Store level, improving both operational efficiency and customer experience.